		<div class="post" id="post-470093">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,470093)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-470093">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/name" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(254716); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=254716&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610223863" alt="name" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=254716)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/name" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(254716); return false;" >name</a></span> <span class="odate time_1241563786 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">05 May 2009 22:49</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-470093">
									

<p>Some I have noticed</p>
<p>Spheres of Doom: This often happens when the writer has a cool effect, (often times something to do with physics) but can't think of an object that fits thematically with that power, so they kind of just take the easy way out and attach it/tack it on to a "glowing mysterious orb". Like its been said before, there's nothing essentially wrong with this, but they're overdone, and most of the time boring- and it seems lazy.</p>
<p>The weirdness can also be added onto random spaces or patches of air, creating anomalous danger zones. Its basically the same concept- a free floating power with no real dramatic connection to an object.</p>
<p>Exploration: There is nothing special about this SCP except that it serves as a gateway into another world- that right away is a potential problem when the focus isn't on the item but on this magical creepy land. And then we all know what happens next:</p>
<p>D class head in</p>
<p>Don't come back</p>
<p>Send them in with ropes around their waists</p>
<p>Ropes pulled back ripped, with blood on the end (gasp!)</p>
<p>Send in drones.</p>
<p>Robot's camera feed dies!</p>
<p>The first couple were good, but now its so formulaic and predictable.</p>

							</div>

								
