				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-rhaomi" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(328504); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=328504&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610223863" alt="Dr Rhaomi" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=328504)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-rhaomi" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(328504); return false;" >Dr Rhaomi</a></span> <span class="odate time_1244433542 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Jun 2009 03:59</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-502750">
									

<p>I strongly suggest this list be rewritten in more straightforward language. Yes, it's pretty funny now, but guidelines aren't meant to be inside-jokey laffs for insiders. They're meant to be crystal-clear distillations of policy. If this is supposed to be a collection of must-read advice for newcomers, why cloak it in a 4chan-esque argot that distracts from its message? Why give people unfamiliar or unamused by that style an excuse for not heeding it?</p>
<p>For instance, for item 1, why not write:</p>
<p><strong>Supernaturally effective weapons, warriors, etc.</strong> - Taking your basic pistol, sword, or suit of armor and making them indestructible, sentient, and/or vastly more destructive might sound cool, but it's been done to death here. Avoid this unless you have a strikingly original idea or angle that hasn't been tried.</p>

							</div>

								
					
